description: Unknown. Perhaps a sailors' alteration of squirt.

entries.meaning: Any of several carnivorous marine cephalopod mollusks, of the order Teuthida, having a mantle, eight arms, and a pair of tentacles
A fishhook with a piece of bright lead, bone, or other substance fastened on its shank to imitate a squid.
(US, military, slang, mildly derogatory) A sailor in the Navy.
(UK, slang, humorous, rare) A quid; one pound sterling.
examples: Can you lend me five squid? I feel like a bacon sarnie.

verbs.description: squid (third-person singular simple present squids, present participle squidding, simple past and past participle squidded)

entries.meaning: (fishing) To fish with the kind of hook called a squid.
(parachuting) To cause squidding (an improper, partial, parachute inflation, that results in the sides of the parachute folding in on the center, and pulsating back and forth).

description: Possibly a blend of stupid and quick; "stupid, quick, under-dressed and imminently dead", a claimed origin, is probably a backronym.

entries.meaning: (slang, motorcycling, derogatory) A motorcyclist, especially a sport biker, characterized by reckless riding and lack of protective gear.
examples: "In my mind, a street squid is anyone who races on the street. Period."1
"squid: a cocky motorcyclist who darts very aggressively through traffic"2
